<paragraph blockId="85.[128,654,213,1064]" pageId="85" pageNumber="85">
In his moving memorial to Doherty, 
<bibRefCitation author="Hartert, E." box="[128,422,598,620]" pageId="85" pageNumber="85" pagination="494 - 506" refId="ref118211" refString="Hartert, E. 1901 c. William Doherty. Obituary. Novitates Zoologicae 8: 494 - 506." type="journal article" year="1901">Hartert (1901c: 503–504)</bibRefCitation>
quoted from Doherty’s letters concerning his whereabouts at the time his last collections were made and (
<bibRefCitation author="Hartert, E." box="[136,362,687,709]" pageId="85" pageNumber="85" pagination="620 - 625" refId="ref118520" refString="Hartert, E. 1902 g. On the birds collected by William Doherty in the Kikuyu Mountains, near Escarpment Station, in British East Africa. Novitates Zoologicae 9: 620 - 625." type="journal article" year="1902">
Hartert, 
<quantity box="[238,310,687,708]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.902" pageId="85" pageNumber="85" unit="g" value="1902.0">1902g</quantity>
: 620
</bibRefCitation>
) made further comments about the ‘‘Escarpment’’ locality. The ‘‘Escarpment’’ of Doherty’s collecting was on the eastern side of the Rift Valley and was not the ‘‘Mau Escarpment,’’ as reported in the original description of this form, which is on the western side. Doherty was in the Kikuyu Mountains near the Escarpment station of the 
<collectingCountry box="[185,279,924,946]" name="Uganda" pageId="85" pageNumber="85">Uganda</collectingCountry>
Railroad at 
<geoCoordinate box="[468,548,924,945]" degrees="01.01" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="85" pageNumber="85" precision="555" value="-1.01">01.01S</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[573,654,924,946]" degrees="36.37" direction="east" orientation="longitude" pageId="85" pageNumber="85" precision="555" value="36.37">36.37E</geoCoordinate>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Polhill, D." box="[136,294,954,976]" pageId="85" pageNumber="85" refId="ref125653" refString="Polhill, D. 1988. Flora of tropical East Africa. Index of collecting localities. Kew, UK: Royal Botanic Gardens, 398 pp." type="book" year="1988">Polhill, 1988</bibRefCitation>
), which was about ‘‘halfway between Ft. Smith (Nairobi) and Naivasha station’’ and was ‘‘in 
<date box="[428,598,1013,1035]" pageId="85" pageNumber="85" value="1900-10">October 1900</date>
the terminus of the railway.’’
</paragraph>
